turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail arrived at a suburban Des Moines, Iowa fruit processing company with an added vehicle, a second Scooby van. The second van was mechanically identical to the original Scooby van, with a nearly identical Secret Service escort vehicle. The reason for the second van is unclear, but it's possible that the Secret Service employs decoy vehicles to inject some mystery into VIPs' travel plans. The two Scooby vans left together in a seven-car motorcade, which also included four black Suburbans and a white minivan. The second van's driver brought up the rear and used blue and red flashing lights to force an Iowa motorist to pull over and allow the van to pass. It's common for the Secret Service to deploy duplicates of aircraft and cars used to transport VIPs, including Marine One, the president's customized helicopter, which usually travels with two decoys.

A mother of six is making a desperate plea for help after a fire left her family without a home. The rented condo in Decatur, Georgia was reduced to a pile of rubble early on Monday morning, and despite efforts to get the children out safely, all of their belongings were destroyed. The mother, Kalimah Dixon, has been staying with a friend far from the children's schools, and is finding it difficult to find a permanent home while unemployed. A GoFundMe page has been started to help the family and has raised $4,619 so far, but housing assistance has been difficult to come by.

An Australian couple, who entered into an international surrogacy arrangement in India, were reportedly told repeatedly that the boy child born through surrogacy would be left stateless. Documents obtained by the ABC reveal that Australian government officials were aware of the case, where the couple returned to Australia with a baby girl while leaving her twin brother behind. The couple had sought citizenship for the baby girl, but informed the consular staff that they would be leaving the boy behind due to financial constraints. The Indian government does not recognise surrogate children as citizens, which meant the boy would be left stateless. The couple had reportedly told consular staff that they wanted a baby girl to complete their family. Chief Justice of the Family Court, Diana Bryant, had expressed concerns that the boy child may have been sold, as consular staff had informed her of their concerns.

Kecil the one-year-old baby orangutan, who had a tough start to life after his natural mother and another surrogate mother rejected him, has found love with second surrogate mother Maggie at Chicago's Brookfield Zoo. Maggie, 53, has proved herself an experienced mother by helping to raise Kecil for the past 10 months, and the two now have an inseparable bond. Kecil and Maggie will be on display at Brookfield Zoo's Tropic World Asia enclosure on Saturday and Sunday between 10am and midday, and will eventually become part of an exhibit with the zoo's other orangutans.

Javier Pastore, the star player of Paris Saint-Germain football club, has dismissed the suggestion from former Manchester United player Eric Cantona that he is the best footballer in the world. Cantona had praised Pastore for his creativity and ability to make

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife, has successfully fought for a decade to change NICE guidelines on when to clamp and cut the umbilical cord. Burleigh believed that clamping the cord too soon after birth was unnatural and may be harmful to the baby. She collected evidence which showed that immediate cord-clamping could deprive a baby of a third of its blood stock and raise the risk of iron deficiency anaemia. The new guidelines state that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby, and it should be clamped within five minutes, but left longer if the mother requests. The change allows mothers to hold their babies while still connected to the umbilical cord. Burleigh faced resistance from colleagues and felt like a whistle-blower. Dr David Hutchon, a retired obstetrician, also supported the change and said that hospitals had blindly clamped and cut within seconds of birth for decades.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to "show no mercy" if French peacekeepers in the Central African Republic are found guilty of raping hungry children for food. Fourteen soldiers have been accused of sexually abusing children as young as nine while they begged for something to eat at a displaced person's center near Bangui airport between December 2013 and June 2014. The French Defense Ministry has denied covering up the scandal after a UN report was leaked and French authorities launched an investigation into the case. UN staff member Anders Kompass was suspended for leaking the report. A French judicial source said six children, four of whom were direct victims and two who were witnesses, testified against the soldiers. The violence in the Central African Republic has largely pitted the Christian majority against mainly Muslim Seleka rebels who led the March 2013 coup against former leader Francois Bozize.

A Texas pastor's wife, Aracely Meza, was arrested and charged with injury to a child by omission after a "resurrection ceremony" was performed on a two-year-old boy who had died. Video footage shows Meza using oils and praying while attempting to bring the boy back to life in a ceremony that lasted for hours. Her husband, Pastor Daniel Meza, was also involved in the ceremony. A witness claimed that the child was possessed by demons and had gone 25 days without food before he died. The home where the ceremony was performed was not registered or zoned to operate as a church. An investigation is underway involving both state and federal authorities.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott led the Scottish charge at the Betfred World Championship. Higgins, a four-time champion, cruised to a 10-5 victory over Robert Milkins, while Dott, a former champion, defeated Ricky Walden 10-8. Higgins is daring to dream of winning a fifth world title and mentioned that winning would be "incredible" and if it happens it would be "beyond his wildest dreams."

Barcelona football players Neymar, Dani Alves, and Adriano posted photos of themselves on Instagram after their victory over Celta Vigo in La Liga, which returned them to the top of the league. The players all played a role in the win and were seen wearing matching denim in the photos. Dani Alves, who has been linked with a move away from the team, commented on the post by saying it was a "great day at work" and a "little training" was needed in the photo. Jeremy Mathieu, who scored the winning goal, admitted that the team played poorly due to the international break but were still able to secure the win. He praised his defensive partner Gerard Pique for his impressive performance during the game.

Jose Mourinho is reportedly planning to sign Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke this summer by offering second-choice left-back Filipe Luis as a makeweight in a part-exchange deal, according to Spanish newspaper AS. Koke, an Atletico academy graduate, has been instrumental as the club reached the final of the Champions League before losing to local rivals Real Madrid last season. His release clause is around £50million, but Chelsea could be willing to pay for him as Mourinho looks to add to a midfield that has looked tired at times this season.

Tom Ballard, an accomplished climber who was just six years old when his mother died attempting to climb K2, plans to conquer the mountain himself 20 years later. His mother, Alison Hargreaves, was only the second person to climb Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen and was regarded as a revered figure in the climbing world. She was swept to her death in 260mph winds on her descent from K2 in 1995. Despite criticism for climbing dangerous peaks while raising a young family, she shrugged off the flak and continued pursuing her passion. Ballard plans to honor his mother's legacy by following in her footsteps and fulfilling what he sees as his destiny to climb K2.

A consortium of companies exploring an area of England called the Weald Basin claims to have discovered up to 100 billion barrels of oil, worth trillions of pounds, which could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. However, industry experts remain skeptical of the claims and warn that only a fraction of the oil may be accessible for extraction. UK Oil & Gas Investments, which has a 30% stake, made the discovery during test drilling in a well five miles from Gatwick Airport, and they believe this site has 'significant daily oil production' potential. The site is situated in the proposed drilling site container, which is now being used for exploration.

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls. The BVA has concluded that the first two years of culling in Somerset and Gloucestershire did not demonstrate that shotting free-running badgers is effective and humane. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. The British government plans to roll out more culls if they win the election, despite criticism from wildlife groups. The BVA urges politicians not to make the culling a party political issue in the run-up to the election. The Environment Secretary has pledged that any future Conservative government will take the difficult decisions to deal with bovine TB.

It is claimed that modern technology is supposed to make our lives easier, but often it creates more pitfalls. Smartphones and social media can cause problems on dates such as texting too quickly, checking Facebook profiles, and taking food photos. Blu e-cigarettes have listed the top ten ways to avoid showing yourself up on a date, including keeping phones off the table, not checking in online, and avoiding updating relationship status on Facebook.

Tottenham will be without Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris for their match against Aston Villa, while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt. Aston Villa will also be without Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair and Carles Gil, but Aly Cissokho could return. Christian Benteke has scored seven goals in his last five Premier League appearances. Tottenham have won their last five PL meetings with Aston Villa, while Aston Villa have conceded three goals in each of their last two Premier League games.

A mother named Jaye Cox made the difficult decision to give birth to her sick baby at 20 weeks due to a serious form of Spina Bifida. After her daughter Annabelle passed away, Jaye contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization that redesigns wedding dresses into outfits for babies who pass away too soon. Angel Gowns delivered Annabelle's dress on the day she was born and Jaye dressed her so the family could spend time with her before burying her. Angel Gowns created a replica dress for the family to keep in their home, and Jaye looks at it every day to remember her daughter. Angel Gowns donates outfits to more than 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia and deals directly with families as well as children charities. The organization can be contacted at [www.angelgownprogram.com.au](http://www.angelgownprogram.com.au).

A black police officer, PC Ronnie Lungu, has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police after he was not promoted due to the colour of his skin. The employment tribunal ruled that the Zimbabwe-born officer was unlawfully discriminated against on grounds of race after his internal assessments were secretly downgraded and derogatory comments were made about him based on his colour. The force has been ordered to review its procedures and training for dealing with discrimination complaints, and to make sure that it tackles any race discrimination in future. The officer still serves as a PC with the force, but he wants reassurance that the force will take complaints of discrimination seriously in future.

A father named KentuckyFriedIdiot taught his newborn daughter how to suck a plastic water bottle and filmed it for a video on YouTube. He demonstrated the trick by gnawing on a drinks container and then prompted his daughter to do the same. The video has been watched over 190,000 times and has received positive comments from viewers who find it adorable and impressive.

A set of rare photographs taken in the 1850s of the city of Bristol, before much of its historic centre was destroyed by bombing in World War II, have surfaced after being put up for auction. The albumen prints, made in the 1870s from the original paper negatives of the early 1850s, show the city's waterfront, city centre, St Mary Redcliffe church, High Street, College Green, St John's Gate, Broad Quay, and Sleep Street. The Fourteen Stars Tavern building, which was pulled down in 1857, and St Peter's Hospital, which was destroyed in the Bristol Blitz in 1940, can also be seen in the shots. The views of some of the buildings, such as St Mary-Le-Port Street, Sleep Street and High Street, have changed dramatically over the past 160 years. The albumen prints are expected to fetch up to £30,000 at auction tomorrow.

Pro-Ukip Businessman Harvey Boulter, who forced Liam Fox to resign as Defence Secretary, is trying to defeat a "golden boy" Tory candidate Tom Tugendhat in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent. Boulter is spending £30,000 on the campaign, and he is motivated by his vendetta against the Tugendhat family, who awarded Liam Fox a six-figure sum in damages in a libel case.

A six-year-old Aston Villa fan named Charlie Pye applied for the manager position at the club after Paul Lambert was sacked. Although he missed out on the job to Tim Sherwood, Sherwood wrote him a letter congratulating him on his credentials and even offered him the role of captain of the team. Despite missing out on the job, Charlie was overjoyed to receive a letter from the manager and still hopes to one day manage the team.

Atletico Madrid defeated Cordoba 2-0 with goals from Antoine Griezmann and Saul Niguez, moving them above Valencia into third place in the La Liga table with 62 points. Valencia have 60 points and can reclaim third spot with a win at home to Villarreal on Sunday. Real Madrid, who have lost three of their last four games, have 64 points and are four behind leaders Barcelona, who play at Celta Vigo on Sunday. Europa League champions Sevilla have 58 points in fifth after beating Athletic Bilbao at home.

An 18-year-old mother of one died after taking M-Cat at a house party. Abby Swinfield, from Castle Donington, was rushed to hospital in the early hours of March 30 and died a week later. Her family believes her drink was spiked, and a 20-year-old girl has been arrested on suspicion of supplying the drug. Post-mortem examination is yet to establish the cause of death. The police have warned about the use of M-Cat in Tamworth after a raid two months ago during which 4lbs of the drug was discovered. M-Cat is a Class B drug and is also known as Meow Meow. The use of M-Cat can cause multiple organ failure and death.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, which has raised concerns for the health of children in the area. Soil underneath a slide at the park showed radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly half the recommended annual limit of exposure for a person. Authorities cordoned off the park after high levels of radiation were detected, but it is not clear why radiation levels were so high. The park has now been fenced off with an orange barricade, and the city has set up a health advice office to answer queries from concerned parents. Japan has seen heightened concern over radiation since the 2011 failure of a nuclear plant in Fukushima.

Amir Khan believes that Kell Brook is only calling him out for a "one big payday" and that he is not a big name in the UK or globally. Khan also feels that Brook's motivation for the fight is not genuine as he is not a big enough name to have a significant impact on his career. Khan has rejected the offer to fight Brook at Wembley in June as it conflicts with his Islamic faith and Ramadan. He also claims that Brook is only trying to win fans by mentioning his name and putting down his opponents. Khan claims that he makes a lot of money regardless of whether he fights Brook and suggests that Brook needs him to make big money.

A Dallas architect has used 14 shipping containers to build a stunning modern three-bedroom home. The 3,700-square-foot PV14 home has a 1,400 sq ft roof deck and a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor, offering stunning views of White Rock Lake and downtown Dallas. Architect Michael Gooden said the designers wanted people to know what they were standing in when they stepped into the home, and thus all the ceilings were left exposed. The shipping container walls were replaced with sheetrock, and spray foam was used to provide insulation. The house's two-story, glass-paneled tower reflects the shape of the pool. After more than two years of design and construction, the couple are preparing to move into their new home.The

Jordan Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool this week, keeping him at the club until 2020. He made a notable impact in his eight appearances since returning from a loan spell at Derby County in January. Liverpool are also expected to announce new contracts for Jordan Henderson and Martin Skrtel this week, while talks are ongoing with defender Jon Flanagan. Standard Chartered has agreed to a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Liverpool reportedly worth £30 million per year. Ibe posted a picture of himself on Instagram enjoying the summer sunshine.

Rik Mayall, the comedian known for his role as Alan B'Stard in "The New Statesman," died suddenly last June, aged 56, without a valid will, meaning that his estate is subject to inheritance tax laws. Mayall's family could potentially avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split up his estate, but the amount of tax payable would depend on the value of his chattels, which would go to his wife under the rules of intestacy. Andrew Kidd, a solicitor, said that Mayall's children would be entitled to an amount of the net estate liable for inheritance tax, while his wife would receive £250,000 plus all his chattels, and the remaining half of the estate go to Mayall's wife, who would receive a life interest in it.

The Air India airline has been evacuating civilians from Yemen's capital Sanaa during a four-hour window provided by the Saudi air force, which is bombing the city in an attempt to drive out the Houthi rebels. As many as 2,500 people have been evacuated by India so far, which has many nationals working in other nations. Most of the passengers on the Air India flights are Indian nationals, but there are also Yemenis and people from other countries who have been working in Yemen. The Air India crew were seen offering drinks to the 188 evacuees on a recent flight as if they were on a vacation flight, but some passengers were already asleep, exhausted by the push to get out of Yemen. The scene has been described as chaotic, with passengers running to board the planes and minimal luggage allowed. Some of those evacuated have built lives in Yemen, with one professor saying he never felt like a foreigner in the country. The Houthis control the airport in Sanaa, but the Saudis are bombing the city, making it necessary to get permission and a specific route for safe landing. The article quotes one professor who is leaving behind a life he built in Yemen, exhausted and jangled by the shelling and lack of electricity. The article ends with the quote of one of the evacuees "Now I can only pray for Yemen and those we left behind."

An Italian priest has been sacked from his position in a religious order in Taranto after an online lover contacted the church authorities with a dossier containing allegations that the priest had taken part in gay orgies with a Swiss Guard. The priest is also accused of engaging in sexual role-play in which his lover played Judas Iscariot and had to atone for his betrayal of Jesus by becoming his slave. The diocese has confirmed that the priest has been dismissed but has denied that any other priests were involved. This is just the latest sex scandal to engulf the Vatican, with controversy surrounding the involvement of the Swiss Guard, who serve as the de facto military of Vatican City.

A new study published in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine and autism, even among children with a higher risk of developing the condition. The study analyzed data from approximately 95,000 young people, all of whom had older siblings with autism. The researchers found no evidence that vaccinating these children increased their risk of developing autism, and that vaccination rates were lower among children with older siblings with autism. The findings are consistent with past studies, which have consistently found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism. Andrew Wakefield, who published a controversial study in 1998 claiming a link between the MMR vaccine and autism, was later proven to have falsified his data and was stripped of his medical license. Despite these findings, concerns about vaccine safety continue to persist, likely due in part to the ease with which misinformation about vaccines can be spread on the internet.

A 12-year-old girl was kidnapped from her home in the Iraq region of Yazidi by ISIS fighters and subjected to beatings and rape. This is one of many harrowing accounts given by women who have escaped captivity by the Islamist organization. The report from Human Rights Watch found that Yazidi women and children were being captured and forced to convert to Islam, marry and be raped repeatedly. The organization is also accused of committing war crimes and possibly crimes against humanity. The survivors of this abuse need better medical and psychological support, as they continue to face trauma after their ordeal.

A shooting at Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, left one person dead on Monday morning. The alleged shooter, Kenneth Stancil, a former student who did not graduate from the college, entered the building at 8am carrying a long-barreled gun and fired one shot, killing a long-time employee in the print shop. A warrant for Stancil's arrest was issued, and he was described as white, approximately 5'11", with a goatee, and a tattoo over his left eye. A manhunt ensued, with students evacuated from the campus and a massive search underway for Stancil. Authorities urged the public not to approach him as he was considered extremely dangerous. It is not known whether Stancil and the victim were connected. The GPD crime lab arrived at the college, and SWAT teams were clearing the campus building by building. According to local media, the entire campus was evacuated and some students and teachers were still trapped inside and trying to get out. The lockdown was lifted as of about 10.30am ET, and college President Kay Albertson said staff and students had been evacuated, with no hostage situation, but some people were still trapped inside. The college is one hour away from Raleigh and has 3,900 students currently enrolled.

The new chief executive of Rotherham Council may be paid up to £40,000 more than the previous chief executive due to "negative publicity" from the grooming scandal. The council's HR chief suggested offering additional incentives to attract candidates, and the council is now offering up to £200,000 compared to the previous £160,000. However, some council members are uncomfortable with the idea. The rest of the council's cabinet resigned in February after a government report found that the council was "not fit for purpose" and "in denial" about exploitation in the area, mainly of white girls by men of Pakistani origin.

Cesc Fabregas will wear a protective face mask made by the Ortholabsport orthopedic center in Milan after breaking his nose during Chelsea's win over Stoke City. The mask is branded with Fabregas's initial and squad number 'C4' and was made by the center's craftsmen Stefano Duchini and Lucilla Pezzoni. Fabregas traveled to Milan with Chelsea medical director Paco Biosca to have the mask fitted. The center has previously worked with Fernando Torres, Petr Cech, Demba Ba, John Terry, and the Italian national team. Fabregas could be ready to play against Queens Park Rangers on Sunday if Jose Mourinho selects him, while John Obi Mikel is expected to return to the team. Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks with hamstring trouble.

Andros Townsend, an England international and Tottenham Hotspur winger, scored a stunning goal in a 1-1 draw against Italy. He said that criticism from commentators like Paul Merson provided motivation for him during the game. This goal came during a season in which Townsend has struggled to match his earlier success with the national team, but he has the support of manager Roy Hodgson.

A man named Joseph O'Riordan is on trial for attempting to murder his cheating wife. He has pleaded not guilty to the charge. The trial is taking place in Brighton Crown Court. Four months after the attack last year, O'Riordan wrote a letter to his wife while in prison, asking her to gather some of his belongings for his trial. The letter was posted on February 4 of this year. O'Riordan's wife, Amanda, was left with life-threatening injuries after being stabbed multiple times with a kitchen knife. She was discovered by emergency services and treated in hospital. The couple had been married for ten years.

The UK is opening its first three proton beam therapy centers, which will be available to NHS cancer patients in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland by 2017. The announcement comes after the successful treatment of five-year-old Ashya King, who received proton beam therapy in Prague after being diagnosed with an aggressive brain tumor. Proton Partners International Ltd, a group formed in the UK, will operate the centers with almost £100 million equity finance provided by investors. The treatment is highly targeted and has a lower risk of side effects, making it effective for treating cancers that affect critical areas, such as brain cancer. However, Cancer Research UK estimates that only one in 100 people would be suitable for proton beam therapy, and there are concerns that the long-term impact of the treatment is not yet known. The NHS currently sends patients deemed appropriate for proton beam therapy to the United States for treatment, but the UK will open its own centers in 2018 to help meet demand.

Ambulance bosses in the UK are recruiting paramedics from Australia, as it is cheaper than training them in Britain. The London Ambulance Service has hired 225 paramedics in one recruitment drive and is considering another trip later this year. The selection process involves practical demonstrations on dummies and an interview, and the paramedics are offered a £30,200 salary. Many UK paramedics are quitting due to stress and frustration, and some are choosing to work as advanced practitioners in less stressful roles. The exodus of paramedics has forced the NHS to recruit abroad.

Chelsea have partnered with Technogym to equip their training ground with state-of-the-art fitness equipment, aiming to stay at the top of the Premier League. Players such as Eden Hazard, Nemanja Matic, and Kurt Zouma have been

It is reported that babies are more curious and aware of their surroundings than we may have initially thought. Recent studies have shown that babies can understand complex social situations from the age of just 13 months old and can even understand the laws of physics, such as the disappearance of a ball through a solid wall. Furthermore, babies have the ability to learn better when they are surprised, using their previous knowledge to form predictions and attempting to figure out what happened. The study also suggests that some information such as maths and physics may be innate to our survival. The results also found that children who can accurately depict the human form at the age of four are more likely to be brighter in their teenage years.

Manny Pacquiao was spotted training in Griffith Park in Los Angeles ahead of his fight against Floyd Mayweather Jr. He trained outdoors to work on his fitness and stamina, shadow boxing in front of spectators and showing off his impressive footwork. Pacquiao also worked on his core strength. He recently revealed the multicolored mouth guard he will wear during the fight. The boxer's focus and determination were evident as he trained with a fitness coach. Pacquiao will face Mayweather in Las Vegas on May 2 in a highly anticipated match.

A cat named Biso was stuck in a hole in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years. He survived thanks to an elderly man who gave him food and water. Animal rights activists began a social media campaign to free him, and on March 12 a maintenance official helped remove part of the wall to rescue Biso. After his rescue, Biso ran away before being caught. Uncle Abdo is still looking for him inside the station.

At least 35 workers were killed in a dairy factory in Yemen when it was hit by an airstrike today as Saudi Arabian warplanes continue to bomb Shiite rebel positions in the country. Today's airstrikes targeted rebel-controlled army camps in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida and hit warehouses belonging to a factory that produces dairy products. The Houthis, who control the capital and several provinces, have been fighting against a Sunni Arab coalition led by Saudi Arabia and backed by the United States. The coalition aims to restore the internationally recognized government of President Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi, who has fled abroad. Yesterday, UNICEF said that 62 children were killed and 30 wounded in the fighting in Yemen over the past week.

A truck crashed on an elevated highway over subway and rail tracks in Boston during the morning rush hour, causing delays for hundreds of commuters. The truck collided with a car and both drivers were taken to the hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. The commuter rail was delayed due to the crash, and replacement shuttle buses were run for southbound passengers. The truck remained on the highway for hours, causing backups in both directions. State troopers are still investigating the incident.

Saracens director of rugby Mark McCall praised his young players after their defeat in the European Rugby Champions Cup semi-final against Clermont and stated that he has no intention of overspending in the competitive post-World Cup transfer market.

The bodies of the four alleged terrorists who committed the Garissa University College attack were paraded in a pickup truck through a Kenyan town and displayed at a primary school. Survivor Cynthia Cheroitich, who hid in a wardrobe for two days, was rescued and taken to a hospital for observation. Four attackers died at Garissa but their nationalities and names have not been revealed. Kenyan troops found four female students alive after the attack, and five suspects have been detained, including three Kenyan citizens of Somali origin. Al-Shabaab has threatened more attacks and warned that "Kenyan cities will run red with blood."

Arsenal must decide whether to sign Petr Cech this summer, who is set to leave Chelsea after losing his number one spot to Thibaut Courtois. Cech will confirm his decision to leave West London in talks with manager Jose Mourinho and is available for transfer, with several clubs interested in signing him. However, Chelsea will demand in excess of £10m for Cech, who is still seen as a world-class goalkeeper in his prime, despite entering the final year of his contract. The Gunners must overcome Chelsea's reluctance to sell to rivals, but if they can, signing Cech would strengthen their team for next season significantly.

Frankie Dettori will no longer ride for Sheik Joaan Al Thani's Al Shaqab operation in France, as the Sheik has signed up Gregory Benoist for that role. Dettori will focus on the British flat season, while Benoist will ride for Al Shaqab in France, with the exception of Treve, who will continue to be ridden by Thierry Jarnet. The decision to hire Benoist was made due to the expansion of Sheik Joaan's operation, which now includes over 80 horses in France and almost 100 in Britain. Despite the change, Dettori is happy with the decision and will still ride British horses which are sent to race in France.

Lois Lilienstein, co-star of "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," has died at 78. She passed away in Toronto from a rare form of cancer. Lilienstein, who was born in Chicago in 1936 and moved to Toronto in 1996, joined Sharon Hampson and Bram Morrison to launch their singing trio in 1978. The Canadian variety show was best known for songs like "Skinnamarink" and "Peanut Butter." Sally Catto, general manager, programming at CBC Television, paid tribute to Lilienstein for her contribution to Canadian kids TV. The show ran on CBC in Canada from 1984 to 1989, before continuing in reruns on Nickelodeon stateside until 1995. Lilienstein left the Sharon, Lois & Bram performance trio in 2000.

French freediver Guillaume Néry jumped into Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas without scuba gear, holding his breath for several minutes before swimming back to the surface. The hole is 660ft deep, and it is filmed that way for artistic reasons, but it's still an incredible feat. To hold his breath for so long, he goes through mind-body control techniques and follows a specific diet and training regimen. Freediving is a sport where divers go without scuba gear and push the limits of apnea. Some divers can hold their breath for more than 20 minutes, with records held by Stig Severinsen.

A suicide bomber affiliated with ISIS in Afghanistan detonated a bomb in front of a bank in Jalalabad, killing at least 33 people and injuring more than 100 others. The attack was claimed by ISIS Wilayat Khorasan, an offshoot of the terrorist group. The Taliban distanced themselves from the attack and condemned it, while the United Nations condemned the violence and the continued use of suicide attacks in Afghanistan. The incident is the first ISIS claim in Afghanistan and highlights growing concerns about ISIS involvement in the region.

Laura Wells, a plus-size model, has launched an eco-friendly swimwear line in collaboration with Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy. The collection is inspired by the ocean and features coral reef designs. The swimsuits are made from 100% recycled materials and come in sizes ranging from 10 to 24. Wells said the primary challenge was finding environmentally-friendly material while keeping prices affordable, but the swimsuits are now available for purchase.

TrackYourDose is an app that records a person's personal radiation exposure from various sources such as medical examinations, changes in location, and flights. The app uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists from the Physikalisch-Technische Bundesanstalt (PTB) in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland. The app tracks cosmic radiation from air travel and accounts for gamma radiation and cosmic radiation on the ground, as well as medical examinations with ionizing radiation. The app measures the ambient dose equivalent in microsieverts (µSv). The total annual radiation exposure of a typical person in Europe is about 2,100 µSv, while the average radiation exposure of someone in the US is 3,600 µSv. Airline pilots are at risk of deadly skin cancer due to cockpit radiation similar to levels from tanning beds.

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility due to a foodborne illness linked to the deaths of three people. Ten products were recalled earlier in March from a production line at the company's headquarters in Brenham, Texas. The recalled ice cream product is not sold in retail locations and is shipped in bulk to hospitals in 23 states. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends that consumers do not eat any Blue Bell brand products made at the company's Oklahoma facility and that retailers and institutions do not sell or serve them. The investigation to determine whether the illnesses are related to exposure to Blue Bell products is ongoing, and the company will conduct a "careful and complete examination" of its Oklahoma plant to determine the exact cause of the contamination.

Jon Hamm, star of Mad Men, has been exposed for his involvement in a hazing scandal during his time at the University of Texas at Austin in 1990. Court documents unearthed claim that Hamm and seven other frat members set fire to a prospective pledge and beat him with a paddle during a hazing ritual gone wrong. The alleged victim claims that Hamm stood on his spine and dragged him by his genitals. The hazing incident resulted in the Sigma Nu fraternity being shut down and the actors arrest warrant being issued in 1992. The charges were eventually dismissed after a plea deal in 1995.

The UK has pledged to protect the Falklands from “Argentinian bullying” after Argentina announced legal action against British firms exploring for oil off the islands. Argentina is taking action against three British and two US companies for exploration activities for fossil fuels on the Argentine continental shelf without obtaining permission. Argentina’s President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner has promised that the islands will form part of the country’s territory again and warned that those who do business with the Falkland Islands could face legal consequences. The UK Foreign Secretary has stated that the islanders have a perfect right to develop their oil and gas industry and that they can rely on the UK to protect them from Argentinian bullying.

Passengers on a Delta Air Lines flight from Tampa to New York experienced a scare when they landed at LaGuardia Airport and firefighters in protective gear surrounded the plane after reports of an odor of smoke. The crew had noticed a "smoky odor in the cockpit" while taxiing to the gate and shut down both engines as a precaution. Firefighters then used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source, and passengers were kept on the plane for about 45 minutes while the situation was being investigated. The plane was taken out of service for inspection and maintenance, and all passengers were eventually able to deplane safely. The safety of customers and crew is always Delta's top priority.

David Luiz has injured his hamstring and will be out for at least four weeks. He posted a picture on Instagram showing a new hairstyle in the style of a man bun, which he calls "Parisien". His teammate Lucas Moura found the hairstyle amusing and posted a picture with Luiz on Instagram. Luiz's injury is a setback for Paris Saint-Germain as they aim to win both the Ligue 1 and Champions League titles this season.

US President Barack Obama stated in his weekly address that diplomacy is the best way to deal with Iran's contested nuclear program. Obama believes a comprehensive, long-term deal is the best option and expects a "robust debate" on the deal in the United States. He will keep Congress apprised of the "substance of the deal."

A 12-year-old girl named Rose McGrath, who has been battling Leukemia for two years, has been kicked out of St. Joseph's Middle School in Battle Creek, Michigan due to her lack of attendance. Despite making many accommodations for her illness, Rose only attended school 32 days this year, which the school said was not enough. Rose's mother Barbara feels as though the school is failing their child and has filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights. Rose's parents say that she is not skipping school to have fun but rather is too sick to attend.

Passive smoking doesn't just affect humans; it also affects plants. Researchers at the Technical University of Braunschweig in Germany found that peppermint plants can take up high concentrations of nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke. They showed for the first time that peppermint plants can take up high concentrations of nicotine from contaminated soils. The team analysed plants in soil mulched with cigarette tobacco for more than nine days to find that the resulting nicotine concentrations in them were several times higher than the maximum residue level set by European authorities. The study suggests that the reported high levels of nicotine in some food crops and plant-derived products may be due to other sources beyond illegal insecticides. The finding highlights the "horizontal transfer of natural products" from one plant to another. The researchers believe this study sheds light on the hitherto unexplained success behind farming practices such as crop rotation and the co-cultivation of certain vegetables.

A video captures a battle between two male chameleons in Madagascar for a female mate. The more aggressive of the two chases his rival out of the tree and along a concrete wall. One of the chameleons twists in pain as the aggressor takes a huge bite out of him during their clash. The video ends as the chameleons clamber onto a tree branch and become obscured by leaves, with the defeated chameleon crawling away.

Jack Cosgrove, a 20-year-old prop from Worcester Warriors, has agreed to join Edinburgh on a two-year deal. He has played nine times for Scotland's Under 20s team and is looking forward to contributing to Edinburgh's success, citing the positive feedback he received from fellow players. He wants to improve his game and learn from the exceptional Alasdair Dickinson.

Aaron Hernandez, the former NFL player convicted of murder, has been moved to the maximum-security Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center near Shirley, Massachusetts, and is being held separately from other prisoners. Hernandez was a heavy user of angel dust, a dangerous drug that causes users to experience hallucinations, paranoia, and violent outbursts. According to sources, Hernandez was using the drug for at least a year before the murder of Odin Lloyd in 2013. The former New England Patriots star was found guilty of the murder and was sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole.

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has revealed that young players from the club's Academy are not yet ready to step into the first-team squad. This suggests that players like Jason Denayer, who is currently on loan at Celtic, may be returning to the club to fill in the gaps. Celtic is keen to retain Denayer's services, but may face an uphill struggle due to City's focus on investing in homegrown talent. Denayer would fit the bill as he hails from Belgium and falls under the 'homegrown' category. A number of young City players, including Karim Rekik and Marcos Lopes, are on loan and may be brought back to the club next season to fill in some of the holes.

Ander Herrera, a midfielder for Manchester United, wears both his first and last name on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons, following a successful spell at Athletic Bilbao where he reached the Copa del Rey and Europa League finals in his debut season. Herrera, who joined Manchester United for £29 million, has recently forced his way into the starting line-up and scored seven goals in all competitions this season. He celebrates his goals with a lot of emotion, and hopes to show even more in the future as Manchester United chases silverware.

Despite suffering a crushing 6-1 defeat at the hands of Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-final, Porto fans gave their team a heroes' welcome upon their return to Portugal. The team bus was met with a cacophony of noise from proud Porto supporters, who chanted and congratulated the team on their impressive Champions League run. Porto coach Julen Lopetegui admitted that Bayern was the better team but praised his players for their performances in the tournament. Star striker Jackson Martinez and other Porto players looked perplexed as they were hugged by fans before boarding the team bus. The fans' passionate support and pride in their team highlighted the strength and resilience of football fandom.

The BBC has faced criticism for creating an online computer game called Syrian Journey, which simulates the difficult journey Syrian refugees face as they try to flee their war-torn country. The game often ends with refugees dying or being sold to militia, leading to backlash from Middle East experts and social media users. The BBC has defended the game, stating that it is meant to show the difficult choices faced by Syrian refugees, and has received a high number of online hits.

Boston Marathon bomber, Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, has been thrown a lifeline by two of his victims, Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who opposed the death penalty as a means of punishment for their attacker. They join the appeals of the Richards family, who lost their 8-year-old son in the blast, and call for Tsarnaev to be sentenced to life in prison without parole. The trial is taking place in Massachusetts, where the death penalty is outlawed, but it is still an option for federal court. Tsarnaev's legal team, lead by Judy Clarke, aims to portray Tsarnaev as a secondary player in his older brother's terrorist plot. Tsarnaev's defense team has attempted to argue that Tsarnaev was gullible and manipulated by his older brother Tamerlan, who died in a shootout with police a few days after the bombing.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife who claimed half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement came before a ruling on whether Giray could become a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company, Euphrates. Ulukaya's company was not an issue in their divorce, but Giray was basing part of her claim on scribbled handwritten notes written off as family expenses. Ulukaya is still considering replacing him as CEO due to a product recall in 2013 that led to negative EBITDA of $87 million in the fourth quarter.

Diego Costa has been diagnosed with a hamstring injury after limping off just 11 minutes into his return from injury in Chelsea's recent match against Stoke City. Despite the injury, Costa is expected to be fit to face Arsenal in a key match in Chelsea's title run-in, with the striker likely to miss the games against Queens Park Rangers and Manchester United before returning for the clash at the Emirates Stadium. Jose Mourinho is unlikely to take any unnecessary risks with his star striker and may decide to use him sparingly for the run-in depending on how the title race pans out. The club is considering giving Costa an extended break between now and the end of the season to help him overcome his hamstring problems and avoid the need for surgery. Loic Remy is likely to lead the line in Chelsea's upcoming match against QPR while Costa is out.

The England C team, which represents non-league players in England, may be scrapped by the Football Association (FA) as part of a spending review to fund new 3G pitches in urban coaching hubs. The team, which plays only a few games a year, is managed by Paul Fairclough and has been in existence since 1979. Former players include George Boyd, Craig Mackail-Smith, and Steve Morison, who all went on to represent their countries at full international level. However, the team did not qualify for this year's International Challenge Trophy semi-finals and there are no more fixtures planned.

James Haskell, the London Wasps captain, showed off his inner Iron Man by dressing up as the character from the new Avengers: Age of Ultron movie and posting it on his Instagram page. The post was accompanied by a message promoting the movie and Haskell's clothing sponsor, Under Armour UK. Haskell originally started his career at Wasps and later played for teams in France, Japan, and New Zealand before returning to England in 2012. Since returning to Wasps, he has become an important part of the England squad, making over 57 appearances to-date.

Police in Australia are urging witnesses to come forward after a video of a middle-aged woman's offensive tirade against a Muslim woman on a public transportation train went viral. In the video, Stacey Eden stands up to the ranting woman after she allegedly called all Muslims ISIS supporters and branded the woman's husband and headscarf "disgusting." Eden recorded a snippet of the conversation, firing back at the woman in defense of the Muslim couple, saying "Have some respect... What's that got to do with this poor lady?" The couple thanked Eden for her stand, and she missed her stop to make sure they were okay. The incident is not being reported to the authorities as of yet.

Ursula Ward, the mother of Odin Lloyd, who was murdered by Aaron Hernandez, is moving forward with a civil lawsuit against Hernandez. She said she wants to look Hernandez in the eye when he testifies during the trial and wants to know what happened. Her lawyer, Douglas Sheff, said they may call Hernandez's former team, the New England Patriots, to testify, and that Hernandez, who is already convicted, will no longer have the protection of the Fifth Amendment. Hernandez was already paid more than $9.2 million of his $40 million contract at the time of the murder. The team dismissed the suit but the NFL Players Association filed a grievance on Hernandez's behalf seeking an additional $6.2 million in guaranteed money.

Britain has struck oil in the Falklands, potentially escalating tensions with Argentina over the ownership of the islands. Argentina has threatened to prosecute oil companies operating in the area and has said it will file a joint legal filing in the coming days to try and block further exploration. The discovery could be worth billions of pounds and heightens fears of renewed conflict over the British overseas territory. Russia has been reportedly helping to re-arm Argentina, which could exacerbate the situation.

A three-legged cat named Freeman was mauled to death by two dogs in a brutal attack captured on CCTV. The attack occurred in a neighbor's front garden in Tarring, West Sussex, and was witnessed by a person who appeared to call over the dogs before collecting them and leaving the cat to die. The cat's owner, Tracy Lynch, was devastated by the attack and the callous behavior of the dog owners. The police are investigating the incident, which took place while the cat's owner was away on vacation, and have identified the dogs as possible Dobermans. Neighbors are mourning the loss of the beloved cat, which was well-known in the area.

A Chinese woman has become an internet sensation in China after posting photos and videos of her close bond with her pet pig, which she has raised since it was a piglet and now weighs 187lbs. She dresses, walks, and even sleeps with the pig every day. She has nicknamed her pet "crazy pig" and has posted pictures of them snuggled up in bed and dressed in a green T-shirt and body harness. She also takes the pig for walks and often gets comments from people praising her unique pet. Her husband is reported to be "tolerant" of the relationship, but her pet dog seems envious.
